Professor Grivetti:<br><br>
You ask perhaps the most difficult of all questions. There is no simplistic answer as you can learn from the postings on this page.<br><br>
I have some thoughts I would like to share.<br><br>
The Vietnam experience must be considered on many levels. <br><br>
The first level is emotional.<br><br>
Vietnam Veretans, like myself, have a strong emotional bond or connection to the events in our lives during the war. The forces of politics, military thought, society, and personal events, triggered very human psychological reactions that haunt many of us, probably forever.<br><br>
Protestors are another group of individuals who became emotionally ensnarled. Their connections are the acts of the war, its events, and its justification. Protestors are divided into two groups, neither having any use for the other. One group protests the war without judging those who prosecuted the war, and the other protests by judging. The bases for the protestor's emotional connections must be carefully considered.<br><br>
A third group of people haunted by the war are those who were victims of the war through personal loss. These individuals lost family and friends, and I am sure are emotionally haunted. These people seem to be the most silent, but are truly deserving consideration.<br><br>
The forth group of people are those who did not participate in the war for many reasons. There appear to be emotional connections through guilt or self serving behavior. <br><br>
The second level is political.<br><br>
The forces of politics shaped the events that influenced the emotional outcomes of the war. The politics are well known, as is the fingerpointing and blame placing aspects that continue to this day. Politically, the issue seems to be a game of musical chairs. Politically, the Presidents, Congresses, businesses, and the Military played roles that were and continue to be controversial.<br><br>
The third level is historical.<br><br>
It is true we can trace the origins of the Vietnam War through the history of Vietnam. I am sure carefull historians can thread back to pre WWWII events and attitudes which explain the causes of the war.<br><br>
I feel to stop at this point, however, is missing the boat. I feel we need to also examine American history to better appreciate the &quot;cultural psychology&quot; at work behind the scenes. Some have suggested to me the Civil War as a model. I feel we need to go back further to the Revolutionary War for more of the truth. I am not an historian, but I have an intuitive idea that the emotions and politics at the time the American people invented &quot;revolutionary&quot; warfare,  tactics, and politics against the British Empire leads us to a point where we can honestly consider that the reason why the Vietnam War continues to haunt Americans is that we were at many levels fighting ourselves, as we continue to do to this day.<br><br>
The physical aspect of the Vietnam War ended over twenty years ago. We now need to actively put to rest the &quot;unburied&quot;.
